channel.title: [ALL] Cached Client Extractor
channel.description:
Well, it says all but it's technically for all current versions of the game. You just download the jar, put it in your .jagex cache folder/runescape directory and run it... in Linux, [code]java -jar client_extractor.jar;[/code] In Winblows.... double click it yeah? It's self explanatory. [hr] Anyway, what this does is simple... It uses lets you unpack your main_cache_file.dat3 into a nice and neat jar file for whatever you want to do with it. I suggest deobbing :) it's different from the normal rs.jar. Some extra methods, classes etc.
I'd say, questions comments.... but all I expect is flamage, no one here is ever satisfied...

I tried with the 474 and the 481 cache. The “client jar’s” are getting bigger based on the revision, but deobfuscated, all of them turn out claiming they are 448 clients.

item.title: [ALL] Cached Client Extractor
item.dc:creator: @henry henry
item.description:
@henry wrote:

[quote=“qauters, post:24, topic:249580”][quote author=henry link=topic=328972.msg2575364#msg2575364 date=1228935767]

What is the benefit of using this client as opposed to the one that is hosted on their site?
[/quote][quote author=cartridges link=topic=328972.msg2572607#msg2572607 date=1228771998]
it’s different from the normal rs.jar. Some extra methods, classes etc.

I meant as in, what are the benefits. What good does extra methods do, you know lol?
Anyways, I’ll just download and take a look for myself.

It’s the HD client, while the ‘normal’ runescape.jar isn’t. Incase you wondered, main_file_cache.dat0 is the old client.
You can also download them from: http://www.moparisthebest.com/rs/bin_gl/pack200tojar/

so the client in .dat3 is the same as the pack200 file?
.dat0, is the old one… in what sense? as in the client before which switch?
[/quote]
.dat3 is the same as pack200 yes, because it’s the cached pack200 which the loader needs.
with .dat0 I meant the low detail client. (before the HD one)

The reason there is a runescape.jar on the server, is because of the non signed version :). Which means no loader.[/quote]

Oh I get it. So technically if you were using an actual loader it would take the client straight from the cache? Ok that makes sense, thanks.

Read full topic
